An abalone is a particular type of shellfish; I find it rather funny looking:

Your goal is to use physical characteristics from a set of abalone to predict the shellfish’s age.

Your code and text should go in the section below (feel free to create sub-sections with the ### command at the start of line, though please note that this is not required):

Lab 02

The goal here is to predict the age variable. We see that this variable is roughly normally distributed with a mode around 10 years:

qplot(age, data = abalone)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 1254 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

Looking at a number of variables, it visually appears that the sheel_weight variable is the most predictive. That is, points deviate from the line the least:

qplot(sheel_weight, age, data = abalone) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## Warning: Removed 1254 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 1254 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

(NOTE: Usually, I would use some proper validation techniques to evaluate this model, but for now a visual argument is fine. Also, I may be wrong about which variable looks the most predictive; it is just a feeling after looking at a few plots. Other choices are not necessarily wrong.)

As we only know how to do univariate models at this point, I will just fit a univariate model using sheel_weight to predict age.

model <- lm(age ~ sheel_weight, data = abalone)
abalone$age_pred <- predict(model, newdata = abalone)

Usually I would finish by showing the RMSE of my prediction on the training set, but as mentioned above we haven’t covered that yet so there is not much more to say.

Submission

The code below assumes that you have adding a prediction named age_pred to every row of the abalone dataset.

submit <- select(abalone, obs_id, age_pred)
write_csv(submit, "class02_submit.csv")
